# Process & Discipline Rules

These rules govern *how* we work, not *what* we build. They apply globally.

## Architecture Decision Records (ADRs)

ADRs document significant decisions so future-you (and future collaborators) can understand why the system is the way it is.

- **Location:** `docs/adr/NNNN-short-title.md` (zero-padded, e.g., `0001-monorepo-structure.md`)
- **Format:** the standard "Context / Decision / Consequences" template
- **When to write one:** any time a decision is non-obvious or has alternatives that were considered and rejected
- **When to reference one:** in code, near the implementation of the decided pattern (`// See ADR-0007: Why we use Qdrant over pgvector`)
- **ADRs are immutable.** When a decision changes, write a new ADR that supersedes the old one. Mark the old one with a `Status: Superseded by ADR-NNNN` line — don't delete or rewrite.

### ADR template

```markdown
# ADR-0007: Use Qdrant as the vector database

## Status

Accepted — 2026-04-15

## Context

We need a vector database to store chunk embeddings and serve semantic search.
Options considered:

- **pgvector** (Postgres extension): simpler infra, weaker filtering/scaling
- **Qdrant**: dedicated vector DB, strong filtering, easy Docker setup
- **Pinecone**: managed, costs money

## Decision

We use Qdrant, self-hosted via Docker.

## Consequences

**Positive:**
- One concept ("collection") for all chunks across services
- Strong metadata filtering matches our hybrid retrieval needs
- Free for solo learning project

**Negative:**
- One more service to operate
- Migration to managed (Qdrant Cloud or Pinecone) requires data export
- Adds a new failure mode separate from Postgres

## Notes

For a project under ~1M chunks with Postgres already in the stack,
pgvector would be a defensible alternative. Document if the choice
should be revisited.
```

### Suggested early ADRs to write

You don't have to write all of these on day one, but as you build, write ADRs for:

- Monorepo vs polyrepo
- Spring Boot version & Java version
- Postgres schema-per-service vs shared schema
- Qdrant vs pgvector
- RabbitMQ vs Kafka
- LLM provider (Anthropic vs OpenAI vs both)
- Embedding model and the implications for re-indexing
- Auth strategy (JWT structure, refresh token storage)
- Streaming protocol (SSE vs WebSocket)
- Reverse proxy / entry point choice (Nginx vs alternatives — see ADR-0003)
- CI provider and pipeline shape
- Local-only vs deployed dev environment

## Git hygiene

- **Conventional commits.** Every commit message starts with `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`, `docs:`, `test:`, `refactor:`, `perf:`, or `build:`. The first line ≤ 72 chars. Body wraps at 72.
- **Branch per feature/fix.** Never commit directly to `main`. Branch names: `feat/streaming-responses`, `fix/duplicate-chunks-on-retry`.
- **Squash merges into main.** Keep `main` history readable; preserve detail in PR descriptions.
- **Tag at phase boundaries.** When a phase from `IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md` is complete, tag the repo (`phase-3-chat-service`). Easy to compare snapshots later.
- **No commented-out code.** Delete it. Git has the history.
- **Each commit should leave the build green.** No "WIP" commits in main. If you're sharing a WIP, it's a draft PR.

## Pull request discipline

Every non-trivial change goes through a PR even on a solo project. The discipline of writing the PR description is the value.

- **PR title** matches the conventional commit summary.
- **PR description** explains *why*, not *what* (the diff shows the what).
- **Checklist:**
  - [ ] Tests added/updated
  - [ ] ADR added/updated if a significant decision
  - [ ] README/docs updated if user-facing
  - [ ] Eval still passes (if RAG-affecting)
  - [ ] No new lint warnings
  - [ ] No secrets committed

## Secrets management

- **Never commit secrets.** Not in code, not in config files, not in `.env`, not in README.
- **`.env` is gitignored.** `.env.example` lists required variable names with placeholder values.
- **Required secrets fail loudly at startup.** Pydantic Settings without a default raises if missing. Same in Spring with `@Validated` config classes.
- **In CI:** GitHub Actions secrets, scoped per environment.
- **Rotate after exposure.** Even if it's "just a dev key," rotate immediately.

## Configuration and environments

- **Three environments to think about:** `dev` (your machine, full stack in Docker), `test` (CI, ephemeral), `prod` (whatever you eventually deploy to, even if just for personal use).
- **Configuration via env vars** in all environments. Defaults in code are for local dev only.
- **Profile-based configs** (Spring profiles, env-specific Pydantic settings) make environment differences explicit.

## Code review with yourself

Solo project, but use the discipline:

- **Read your own diff before merging.** Out loud, slowly. You catch dumb things this way.
- **Pretend a senior is reviewing.** Would they ask "why did you do it this way"? Add a comment or ADR before they do.
- **Resist scope creep.** If you find a bug while building feature X, file an issue and fix it in a separate PR.

## Documentation alongside code

- **Each service has its own README.** What it does, how to run it, how to test it, what env vars it needs.
- **Public functions/methods have docstrings/Javadoc.** Explain *why* the function exists and any non-obvious contract details. Avoid restating the signature.
- **Complex algorithms have comment headers** describing the approach before the code.
- **The architecture diagram lives in the repo** as `docs/architecture.svg` and is referenced from the root README.

## Learning notes

This project is for learning. Capture what you learn:

- **`docs/learnings/`** is a directory for learning notes. Markdown files, dated and titled.
  Example: `2026-05-12-why-async-postgres-needs-asyncpg.md`
- **Write one when:** you got stuck for >30 minutes, you discovered a non-obvious fact, you made a mistake worth remembering.
- **Format is freeform** but include:
  - Symptom you saw
  - What you tried
  - What worked
  - The general lesson
- **These are not ADRs.** ADRs document decisions; learnings document insights.

## When the AI suggests a shortcut

If a request to Cursor (or a Cursor suggestion) would compromise these rules — skip a test, use `any`, skip ADR for a big decision, hard-code a secret, mix planes — push back. Either:

1. Suggest the proper version with a brief explanation of why the shortcut hurts long-term.
2. Offer a minimal version of the proper approach if scope is the real concern.
3. Ask whether the user wants to proceed with the shortcut anyway (they might; it's their call) — but note it explicitly so they make the choice consciously.

## Definition of done

A piece of work is done when:

- [ ] Code is written and passes lint + typecheck
- [ ] Tests are written and pass
- [ ] Integration tests touch real infrastructure (Testcontainers) where applicable
- [ ] A `// LEARNING:` comment is added if the pattern is non-obvious
- [ ] An ADR is written if a significant decision was made
- [ ] README is updated if anything user-facing changed
- [ ] A PR is opened with a clear description
- [ ] CI is green
- [ ] Future-you can understand the change in 6 months

"It works on my machine" is not done.
